</tt><p>
April 28, 1997<br><br>
                       Touring war wall ends some<br>
                       barriers <br><br>
                       CULTURE: Vietnamese attend observance          <br>
                       for the fall<br>
                       of Saigon with U.S. war veterans.<br><br>
                       By KIMBERLY KINDY<br>
                       The Orange County Register<br><br>
                       Tears filled Minh Duc Vo's eyes as she reached down to straighten a small<br>
                       Vietnamese flag, one of dozens lining a wall filled with names of<br>
                       American men who died fighting for her home country.<br><br>
                       &quot;I was a nurse's aide in the U.S. naval hospital. I saw too many of these<br>
                       men die in front of my eyes,&quot; said Vo, burying her face in a handkerchief<br>
                       in front of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Moving Wall in Westminster.<br>
                       &quot;It has brought back memories. ... They died for nothing.&quot;<br><br>
                       Vo joined hundreds of other Vietnamese families and American war<br>
                       veterans Sunday at the Westminster Civic Center to remember Saigon's<br>
                       fall to Communist forces in 1975.<br><br>
                       The event was organized by the Vietnamese Community of Southern<br>
                       California.<br><br>
                       American veterans said the surrender of Saigon represented their greatest<br>
                       defeat, epitomizing the pointless loss of life in a war they still struggle to<br>
                       understand. For the Vietnamese who fled to America, it's when their<br>
                       country was lost.<br><br>
                       The two groups gathered for speeches, then slowly walked by the wall,<br>
                       which lists the 58,202 American soldiers who died in the Vietnam War.<br>
                       They admitted that sharing the pain of the war has been difficult, and<br>
                       Sunday's event was meant to change that.<br><br>
                       &quot;Some blame them for having to fight their war,&quot; said Charles Randazzo,<br>
                       explaining how some American veterans feel toward the Vietnamese<br>
                       people. &quot;What they have done here today is great. It shows appreciation<br>
                       that we fought for them.&quot;<br><br>
                       Peter Nguyen of Westminster, who helped organize the event, said he has<br>
                       felt the anger of U.S. war veterans for years and was at first afraid to<br>
                       bring the groups together.<br><br>
                       &quot;I had rocks thrown at me and they called me a coward because I left my<br>
                       country,&quot; Nguyen said. &quot;I was just 12 years old and I left six hours after<br>
                       the invasion of South Vietnam.&quot;<br><br>
                       Ethnic relations in the city became strained as the Vietnamese group<br>
                       announced its plans. The organizers petitioned the Westminster City<br>
                       Council for permission to hang Vietnamese and American flags on utility<br>
                       poles throughout the city for two weeks preceding the event.<br><br>
                       The request was denied. On Sunday, both flags hung together but only<br>
                       from a few light posts in the Civic Center parking lot.<br><br>
                       Behind the wall, large American flags waved. Dotting the base of the wall<br>
                       were small yellow and red paper Vietnamese flags.<br><br>
                       Chi Huynh, president of the Vietnamese Association of Flyers, passed<br>
                       over the observance in his Cessna C-152.<br><br>
                       He said the main purpose for the event is the same each year-- to educate<br>
                       Vietnamese youth to petition for democracy so that some day they might<br>
                       return home.<br><br>
                       He encouraged them to fight decisions that will legitimize or give power<br>
                       to the current Vietnamese government, citing President Clinton's decision<br>
                       earlier this month to appoint the first U.S. ambassador to postwar<br>
                       Vietnam as a bad sign.<br><br>
                       &quot;We are all here temporarily,&quot; Huynh said. &quot;We can't return to our<br>
                       country until democracy is restored and that doesn't come by itself.&quot;<br><br>
                       The wall moves on to Findlay, Ohio, on its tour across the country. It<br>
                       returns to Orange County on Veterans Day at Knott's Berry Farm.
